steps.description:
Go to the "Create" tab, then click on "plane" in standard primitives. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/bd\/2.-create-plane.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/bd\/2.-create-plane.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":622,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":1027.5510204081634,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}
Click and drag in the viewport, then center it in x, y & z axis. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/3b\/6.-Center-the-plane.jpg\/460px-6.-Center-the-plane.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/3b\/6.-Center-the-plane.jpg\/760px-6.-Center-the-plane.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Right click on the up-down arrows in the x, y & z field to position the plane at zero.

Click on the empty field near diffuse color. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/6\/65\/9.-Choose-diffuse.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/6\/65\/9.-Choose-diffuse.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":282,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":465.39325842696627,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click the "+" on General to open options in the Material/Map Browser. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/22\/10.-Click-General.png\/460px-10.-Click-General.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/2\/22\/10.-Click-General.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":163,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":269.45454545454544,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Double click on bitmap. Wait for material browser to open. Navigate to the folder and double click your reference image. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/84\/9.-Select-Image.jpg\/460px-9.-Select-Image.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/84\/9.-Select-Image.jpg\/760px-9.-Select-Image.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on Assign material to selection. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/a\/a7\/11.-assign-material.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/a\/a7\/11.-assign-material.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":192,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":316.5133171912833,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on Show shaded material in viewport. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/0\/00\/11.-show-material.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/0\/00\/11.-show-material.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":192,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":316.5133171912833,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Interchange length and width of the plane, if the image gets stretched as shown above.

Select rotate tool (keyboard shortcut R). Select angle snap to rotate in 5 degree increments for ease (keyboard shortcut A). Rotate 90 degrees on the z-axis. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/12.-Rotate.jpg\/460px-12.-Rotate.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/31\/12.-Rotate.jpg\/760px-12.-Rotate.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Rotate 90 degrees on y-axis. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/0b\/13.-Rotate-again.jpg\/460px-13.-Rotate-again.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/0\/0b\/13.-Rotate-again.jpg\/760px-13.-Rotate-again.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Select move tool (keyboard shortcut W), then move the plane back on its x-axis. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/26\/14.-Push-back.jpg\/460px-14.-Push-back.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/26\/14.-Push-back.jpg\/760px-14.-Push-back.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on vertex button from edit poly modifier. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/d\/de\/24.-Select-vertex.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/d\/de\/24.-Select-vertex.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":138,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":228.3743842364532,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click and drag to select all the top vertices of the cylinder. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/47\/21.-Select-top-vertices.jpg\/460px-21.-Select-top-vertices.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/4\/47\/21.-Select-top-vertices.jpg\/760px-21.-Select-top-vertices.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on the small button next to extrude. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/4\/4b\/23.-Extrude-setting.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/4\/4b\/23.-Extrude-setting.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":346,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":571.1242603550296,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Extrude the vertices using setting box opened. Do twice since the bullet casing has two bends at the top. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/6\/62\/25.-Extrude-sett.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/6\/62\/25.-Extrude-sett.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":552,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":912,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Select all the bottom vertices. Align the selected vertices to top part of the notch, on the z axis, as shown below with the reference image. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/57\/23.-Extrude-for-bottom.jpg\/460px-23.-Extrude-for-bottom.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/57\/23.-Extrude-for-bottom.jpg\/760px-23.-Extrude-for-bottom.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Extrude again. Do it twice exactly to match the edges for the notch. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/b2\/24.-Extrude-twice.jpg\/460px-24.-Extrude-twice.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/b2\/24.-Extrude-twice.jpg\/760px-24.-Extrude-twice.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on faces button in modifier panel. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/b3\/26.-select-faces.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/b3\/26.-select-faces.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":176,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":290.4712041884817,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Then select the ring of faces (one up from bottom) as shown in the picture. Extrude the faces negatively. In this image below a value of -5mm is used. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a0\/25.-Select-face-and-negative-extrude.jpg\/460px-25.-Select-face-and-negative-extrude.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a0\/25.-Select-face-and-negative-extrude.jpg\/760px-25.-Select-face-and-negative-extrude.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Select bottom most ring of faces. Scale them on xy axis by clicking on the select & uniform scale in toolbar (keyboard shortcut R). Hover mouse on xy plane of the pivot as shown in the figure. Then click and drag to scale. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/ec\/26.-Scale-bottom.jpg\/460px-26.-Scale-bottom.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/ec\/26.-Scale-bottom.jpg\/760px-26.-Scale-bottom.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Go to Modify panel, then click on the modifier list. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/7\/70\/20.-Modifier-panel.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/7\/70\/20.-Modifier-panel.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":273,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":450.6194690265487,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Select "Edit poly" from the drop down menu. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/5\/52\/21.-add-edit-poly.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/5\/52\/21.-add-edit-poly.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":832,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":1375.2380952380952,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Then repeat step 3 in Part 2 for see through.

Click on face select tool. Select the top face of bullet. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/9d\/33.-Delete-top-face.jpg\/460px-33.-Delete-top-face.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/9\/9d\/33.-Delete-top-face.jpg\/760px-33.-Delete-top-face.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Delete the top face. Select all the top vertices. Do a negative extrude as much as possible with a very small gap. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1c\/34.-Neg-extr.jpg\/460px-34.-Neg-extr.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/1\/1c\/34.-Neg-extr.jpg\/760px-34.-Neg-extr.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on the Weld tool in modifiers panel. Weld all these extruded top vertices. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/c2\/35.-Weld.jpg\/460px-35.-Weld.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/c2\/35.-Weld.jpg\/760px-35.-Weld.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Select and pull the new welded vertice to the top using the move tool. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/86\/36.-Pull-upward.jpg\/460px-36.-Pull-upward.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/86\/36.-Pull-upward.jpg\/760px-36.-Pull-upward.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click modifier list from the modifier panel. Select and add "Turbosmooth" from the drop down menu. This will give the bullet a smooth look. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/c4\/37.-Turbo-smth-with-2-iter.jpg\/460px-37.-Turbo-smth-with-2-iter.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/c\/c4\/37.-Turbo-smth-with-2-iter.jpg\/760px-37.-Turbo-smth-with-2-iter.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click on Modeling panel in toolbar. Click Edit>Swiftloop. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2b\/30.-Swift-Loop.jpg\/460px-30.-Swift-Loop.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2b\/30.-Swift-Loop.jpg\/760px-30.-Swift-Loop.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Add loop cuts at all the edges of the case notch and at the bottom. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6a\/40.-Add-extra-loop-cuts.jpg\/460px-40.-Add-extra-loop-cuts.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/6\/6a\/40.-Add-extra-loop-cuts.jpg\/760px-40.-Add-extra-loop-cuts.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}
