{"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8b\/42..jpg\/460px-42..jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/8\/8b\/42..jpg\/760px-42..jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

text:
 Set up your Work Use a reference image. This is required for modelling. Go to the web and download an image showing the schematic of a bullet with its case. Check the dimensions of your reference image. Right click on the reference image. Then, click properties and go to the details tab. Start 3DS Max.  Change your view to Perspective for easy editing. Click on the bottom right window, then press Alt + W on keyboard to maximize your perspective view.. Change the unit setup in 3DS Max. Go to Customize > Units Setup. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/c\/c9\/6.-Click-customize.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/c\/c9\/6.-Click-customize.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":515,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":850.4180064308682,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Change the Display Unit Scale to Metric and choose "millimeters" from drop down. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/f\/f2\/7.-Change-units.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/f\/f2\/7.-Change-units.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":624,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":1030.5501618122978,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Create a plane. Go to the "Create" tab, then click on "plane" in standard primitives. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/bd\/2.-create-plane.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/bd\/2.-create-plane.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":622,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":1027.5510204081634,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}
Click and drag in the viewport, then center it in x, y & z axis. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/3b\/6.-Center-the-plane.jpg\/460px-6.-Center-the-plane.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/3\/3b\/6.-Center-the-plane.jpg\/760px-6.-Center-the-plane.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":259,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":428.02197802197804,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Right click on the up-down arrows in the x, y & z field to position the plane at zero. Modify the length and width of your plane from the modify panel. Divide your reference image length and width pixel count by 10 (eg: 506 pixels will be 50.6mm) and change the length and width parameters of plane in mm. This will allow you to use the image without altering the aspect ratio of the picture. Open the compact material panel. Click rendering in toolbar. Click material editor and choose Compact material editor. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/b\/b7\/8.-open-material-editor.png\/460px-8.-open-material-editor.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/b\/b7\/8.-open-material-editor.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":647,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":1069.3467336683418,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"} Add your reference image to the plane. Click on the empty field near diffuse color. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/6\/65\/9.-Choose-diffuse.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/6\/65\/9.-Choose-diffuse.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":282,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":465.39325842696627,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Click the "+" on General to open options in the Material/Map Browser. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/22\/10.-Click-General.png\/460px-10.-Click-General.png","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/2\/22\/10.-Click-General.png","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":163,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":269.45454545454544,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fair_use\">Fair Use<\/a> (screenshot)<br>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

